<chapter xml:id="chap-geometry">
<title>Geometry</title>
<introduction> <p> ... </p> </introduction>

<p>
Now we attempt to leave behind relationships between numbers and between
symbols for between shapes and space.  We will try, but we still will
not make it far.  Even as we become more interested in the properties of
shapes and the connections between different shapes, numbers, symbols,
and formulas will play a role in helping us understand and keep track of
various details.</p>

<section xml:id="sub-Square-dancing">
<title> Square dancing </title>
<introduction> <p> ... </p> </introduction>

<p>We talked about how to use shapes to prove that <me>a^2+b^2 = c^2</me> when
<m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are perpendicular sides of a triangle and <m>c</m> is the
hypotenuse.</p>

<p>Given confirmation that various angles were the same in a set of two
smaller, subdivided triangles, we looked at a more mechanical derivation
of the theorem (see the footnotes of the book, actually).</p>

